\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/lf.slopes}{Slopes}}
\begin{definition}\label{lf.slopes}
\uses{lf.discriminant_exponent,lf.hidden_slopes,lf.padic_field,lf.residue_field_degree,lf.tame_degree}
Let $L/K$ be an extension of \hyperref[lf.padic_field]{$p$-adic fields}.
For each subextension $E/K$ of $L/K$ we plot the point \((n_E,c_E)\),
where $n_E=[E:K]$ and $c_E$ is the
\hyperref[lf.discriminant_exponent]{discriminant exponent} of $E/K$.
Let $B$ be the boundary of the lower convex hull of these points.  The slopes
of the segments of $B$ are called the \textbf{Artin slopes} of
$L/K$, and those which are greater than 1 are the \textbf{wild Artin slopes}.  If a segment corresponding to a wild slope runs from \((n_1, c_1)\) to \((n_2, c_2)\) then $n_2/n_1=p^m$
for some $m\in\N$, and the corresponding Artin slope is repeated $m$
times.  The \textbf{Swan slopes} of $L/K$ are obtained by subtracting $1$ from each Artin slope, and the \textbf{wild Swan slopes} are precisely the positive ones.  The Artin slopes and Swan
slopes of $L/K$ are also referred to as the \textbf{visible Artin slopes} and the
\textbf{visible Swan slopes}.  This is to distinguish them from the
\hyperref[lf.hidden_slopes]{hidden slopes} of $L/K$.

Let $f$ be the \hyperref[lf.residue_field_degree]{residue field degree}, let $\epsilon$ be the \hyperref[lf.tame_degree]{tame degree} of $L/K$, and let $a_1\le a_2\le\dots\le a_w$ be the wild Artin slopes of $L/K$.
The \textbf{Artin slope content} of $L/K$ is the collection of data
$[a_1,\dots,a_w]_{\epsilon}^f$.  The \textbf{Swan slope content} of $L/K$ is $[s_1,\dots,s_w]_{\epsilon}^f$, where $s_1,\dots,s_w$ are the wild Swan slopes of
$L/K$.

The Swan slopes are the same as the positive upper ramification jumps of
$L/K$.  In the case where $L/K$ is a Galois extension these are defined for
instance in Chapter IV of Serre's <i>Local Fields</i>
\cite{doi:10.1007/978-1-4757-5673-9,MR:0554237}.  For the general case where
$L/K$ is separable but not necessarily Galois see the appendix to Deligne
\cite{MR:0771673}.
\end{definition}
